tes dilemmas for both national policymakers who confront the "mixed blessing" of capital inflows and the international institutions that manage the recurrent crises.The authors—leading economists and political scientists—examine private capital flows and their consequences in Latin America, Pacific Asia, and East Europe, placing current cycles of lending in historical perspective. National governments have used a variety of strategies to deal with capital-account instability. The authors evaluate those responses, prescribe new alternatives, and consider whether the new circumstances require novel international policies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapital movementszDeveloping countries. 0aInternational finance. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aBuyske, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabezas, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichengreen, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishlow, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelb, Leslie H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahler, Miles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahler, Miles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaxfield, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCulloch, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetri, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReinhart, Carmen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReinhart, Vincent Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul